<P>
 Chase Manhattan to Enter Securities Trade: The New York bank said it has 
federal permission to begin underwriting and trading in corporate 
securities.Such approval represents an important step for commercial banks away 
from restrictions -- dating back to the 1930s -- on the involvement by banks in 
securities-related activities. Chase, Citicorp and a few other banks have 
applied for and received permission to underwrite corporate debt securities 
through separately capitalized subsidiaries. They may issue debt in the form of 
securities for public and private companies. Some other banks, including J.P. 
Morgan & Co., Bankers Trust Co., Daughin Deposit Corp., NationsBank and 
Chemical Banking Corp., have received approval to underwrite equities. 
